// (no explicit URL — Kestrel defaulted to :5000 / :5001)

// AFTER
var port = Environment.GetEnvironmentVariable("PORT") ?? "8080";
builder.WebHost.UseUrls($"http://0.0.0.0:{port}");
2. Hardcoded localhost database credentials — appsettings.json
Root cause: The connection string Host=localhost;Password=123123 is committed to source control. On Railway, the database host is never localhost.

Fix applied:

appsettings.json → connection string emptied (safe public default)
appsettings.Development.json → localhost string moved here (dev-only, git-ignored)
Program.cs → reads DATABASE_URL (Railway plugin) first, then ConnectionStrings__Default (Railway secret), then appsettings fallback
csharp
var connectionString =
    Environment.GetEnvironmentVariable("DATABASE_URL")
    ?? Environment.GetEnvironmentVariable("ConnectionStrings__Default")
    ?? builder.Configuration.GetConnectionString("Default")
    ?? throw new InvalidOperationException("No connection string found.");
3. AppContext.SetSwitch called after builder construction — Program.cs
Root cause: The Npgsql legacy timestamp switch was set after CreateBuilder(), meaning the DI container could initialize Npgsql before the switch took effect in async scenarios.

Fix: Moved to the very first line of Program.cs, before any builder call.

4. Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore.SqlServer package in .csproj
Root cause: The project uses PostgreSQL exclusively, but the SQL Server provider was also referenced. On a Linux container this adds ~15 MB of dead weight and can cause native library resolution warnings.

Fix in .csproj: Package removed entirely.

5. Npgsql.EntityFrameworkCore.PostgreSQL.Design v1.1.0 — .csproj
Root cause: This package targets EF Core 1.x and is completely obsolete. It conflicts with modern Npgsql and can break the build.

Fix in .csproj: Package removed. The Design functionality is included in Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore.Design (already present).

6. No auto-migration on startup
Root cause: Without MigrateAsync(), the database schema on Railway's fresh PostgreSQL instance is empty — every request will throw relation "..." does not exist.

Fix in Program.cs:

